pull_request.title: l4t-extlinux-config: add support for OVERLAYS
pull_request.body:
This PR adds support for OVERLAYS in extlinux.conf to meta-tegra.  I haven't found this feature officially documented anywhere but it's referenced in forums like https://forums.developer.nvidia.com/t/place-custom-overlay-file-via-extlinux-conf/298287.  This feature is useful for anyone who wants to be able to modify devicetree overlays listed in `TEGRA_PLUGIN_MANAGER_OVERLAYS` without the necessity to do a capsule update, either by hand modifying in their `/boot` directory or using the `TEGRA_SWUPDATE_BOOTLOADER_INSTALL_ONLY_IF_DIFFERENT` feature of the [swupdate demo](https://github.com/OE4T/tegra-demo-distro/tree/master/layers/meta-tegrademo/dynamic-layers/meta-swupdate#tegra_swupdate_bootloader_install_only_if_different).

If/when this commit goes in I have a backport I'm planning for r35 branches which will also pull in a rebased commit from r36 branches of edk2-nvidia to support this on Jetpack 5 targets as well.  I've tested to ensure this works on kirkstone, see https://github.com/OE4T/meta-tegra/compare/kirkstone...Trellis-Logic:meta-tegra:kirkstone+overlays-extlinux-feature?expand=1 for preview. This means all device tree content should be able to be synchronized with rootfs content across the Jetpack 5/6 release series.

For those who don't specify `USE_OVERLAYS_IN_EXTLINUX = "1"` there should be no change with this PR, devicetree overlays will continue to come from spiflash only.

One thing I didn't take on with this task but could... I don't believe the logic in `do_concat_dtb_overlays` [here](https://github.com/OE4T/meta-tegra/blob/651e0898cb47ccc86c0ed5c7617fcfeadd7fda1f/recipes-bsp/uefi/l4t-launcher-extlinux.bb#L50-L55) actually is used by anything as far as I can tell. I could rename this function to reference its dual use for copying overlays or remove the concatenate part.

If/when this goes in I'll also reference it in the wiki page at https://github.com/OE4T/meta-tegra/wiki/Using-device-tree-overlays or I could work on a reorg/retitle of this page since it's about more than just devicetree overlays at this point.

# Commit Text
As discussed in [1], overlay source on JP5/6 targets appears to come only from the update capsule content in spi flash and not from either the content appended to the extlinux dtb.  This means if a slot switch occurs the devicetree overlay content used will match the last capsule update as opposed to the content overlayed on the dtb file referenced in extlinux.conf.  This also means slot switches don't apply dtb overlay changes when using slot switching instead of capsule update as a software update strategy for non bootloader components (see the TEGRA_SWUPDATE_BOOTLOADER_INSTALL_ONLY_IF_DIFFERENT feature at [2] for example).

With this patch, add support for writing the OVERLAYS value in the extlinux.conf file.  Specifiying

```
UBOOT_EXTLINUX_FDT = "/boot/${DTBFILE}"
USE_OVERLAYS_IN_EXTLINUX = "1"
```
in your local.conf or machine config will
* Copy all .dtbo files in TEGRA_PLUGIN_MANAGER_OVERLAYS list into the /boot directory of the rootfs when building the l4t-launcher-extlinux.
* Reference each .dtbo file in the extlinux.conf file, applying it as a part of the ExtLinuxBoot process in L4TLauncher.

1: https://matrix.to/#/!YBfWVpJwNVtkmqVCPS:gitter.im/$OJAkyoJCMQDfiamxJGULUseBv7vgH2fJy9cVLMbhh4g?via=gitter.im&via=matrix.org&via=3dvisionlabs.com
2: https://github.com/OE4T/tegra-demo-distro/tree/master/layers/meta-tegrademo/dynamic-layers/meta-swupdate#tegra_swupdate_bootloader_install_only_if_different

# Testing

Testing on master with jetson-orin-nano-devkit-nvme

1. Set in the local.conf:
```
UBOOT_EXTLINUX_FDT = "/boot/${DTBFILE}"
USE_OVERLAYS_IN_EXTLINUX = "1"
IMAGE_INSTALL:append = " dtc"
```

2. After boot, generate a DTS copy of the first overlay using logic like this:
```
cat /boot/extlinux/extlinux.conf | sed -n 's/.*OVERLAYS[[:space:]]\+\([^,]*\).*/\1/p' | xargs cat | dtc -I dtb -O dts >  /boot/first-overlay-original.dts && cp /boot/first-overlay-original.dts /boot/first-overlay-modified.dts
```
3. Modify the /boot/first-overlay-modified.dts by adding a line `test = "overlay-modified"`.  The resulting difference should look like this:
```
diff /boot/first-overlay-original.dts /boot/first-overlay-modified.dts
--- /boot/first-overlay-original.dts
+++ /boot/first-overlay-modified.dts
@@ -7,6 +7,7 @@
                target-path = "/";

                __overlay__ {
+                        test = "overlay-modified";

                        reserved-memory {
                                #address-cells = <0x02>;

```
4. Convert the modified dts file into the first overlay in the OVERLAYS list:
```
dtc -I dts -O dtb -o /boot/first-overlay-modified.dtbo  /boot/first-overlay-modified.dts 
cat /boot/extlinux/extlinux.conf | sed -n 's/.*OVERLAYS[[:space:]]\+\([^,]*\).*/\1/p' | xargs cp /boot/first-overlay-modified.dtbo
```
5. reboot
6. Verify the test marker is added to the device-tree from the overlay
```
root@jetson-orin-nano-devkit-nvme:~# cat /proc/device-tree/test
overlay-modified
```

comment.body: I'd recommend dropping this variable, and keeping the extlinux-provided overlays separate from the TEGRA_PLUGIN_MANAGER ones. That's in keeping with the NVIDIA implementation - the overlays attached to the bootloader's DTB are *always* applied; any overlays specified in the extlinux config are in addition to those (and only apply to the kernel DTB).

comment.body:
I don't mind using a variable to specify the path, but:
*  The way this works is specific to L4TLauncher's implementation, so the prefix should have TEGRA or L4T in it, rather than UBOOT... since we're including the path in for each of the items, rather than the U-Boot-style implementation of providing an FDTDIR entry in the configuration and leaving the individual items as plain file names.
* The same path is likely to apply to the FDT as well as any overlay, so it would be nice to have one for the FDT and have the one for overlays default to the same value
* It would be helpful to have one for the kernel image, also, and maybe have that be the default for the FDT-related one (and `/boot` should be the `??=` default)

The main reason for setting this variable would be if you configure your system to have a separate partition for `/boot`, which would likely be the case if you're setting up for LUKS encryption of your rootfs.

I have some notes in-line, but overall...

I'd appreciate it if this could be split into multiple commits.

1.  Refactor the library functions
2. Get rid of the `do_concat_dtb_overlays` function, since we've established that it's completely unnecessary - L4TLauncher doesn't process overlays concatenated to the kernel DTB that it reads, either from the extlinux config, nor from the android kernel-dtb partition. Instead, just install the dtb if UBOOT_EXTLINUX_FDT is set.
3. Add the overlay support in the extlinux config. This should be kept separate from `TEGRA_PLUGIN_MANAGER_OVERLAYS`, since the extlinux ones are applied *in addition* to the ones attached to the bootloader's DTB.
4. Maybe switch to setting `UBOOT_EXTLINUX_FDT` by default for the device tree, too, for consistency. Just seems odd to have overlays in the config with out the base device tree.

And can you verify that all this works with UEFI signing enabled - i.e., that signing happens for all the overlays, so they all get their `.dtbo.sig` files installed?

pull_request.title: l4t-extlinux-config: add support for OVERLAYS
pull_request.body:
This PR adds support for OVERLAYS in extlinux.conf to meta-tegra.  I haven't found this feature officially documented anywhere but it's referenced in forums like https://forums.developer.nvidia.com/t/place-custom-overlay-file-via-extlinux-conf/298287.  This feature is useful for anyone who wants to be able to modify devicetree overlays listed in `TEGRA_PLUGIN_MANAGER_OVERLAYS` without the necessity to do a capsule update, either by hand modifying in their `/boot` directory or using the `TEGRA_SWUPDATE_BOOTLOADER_INSTALL_ONLY_IF_DIFFERENT` feature of the [swupdate demo](https://github.com/OE4T/tegra-demo-distro/tree/master/layers/meta-tegrademo/dynamic-layers/meta-swupdate#tegra_swupdate_bootloader_install_only_if_different).

If/when this commit goes in I have a backport I'm planning for r35 branches which will also pull in a rebased commit from r36 branches of edk2-nvidia to support this on Jetpack 5 targets as well.  I've tested to ensure this works on kirkstone, see https://github.com/OE4T/meta-tegra/compare/kirkstone...Trellis-Logic:meta-tegra:kirkstone+overlays-extlinux-feature?expand=1 for preview. This means all device tree content should be able to be synchronized with rootfs content across the Jetpack 5/6 release series.

For those who don't specify `USE_OVERLAYS_IN_EXTLINUX = "1"` there should be no change with this PR, devicetree overlays will continue to come from spiflash only.

One thing I didn't take on with this task but could... I don't believe the logic in `do_concat_dtb_overlays` [here](https://github.com/OE4T/meta-tegra/blob/651e0898cb47ccc86c0ed5c7617fcfeadd7fda1f/recipes-bsp/uefi/l4t-launcher-extlinux.bb#L50-L55) actually is used by anything as far as I can tell. I could rename this function to reference its dual use for copying overlays or remove the concatenate part.

If/when this goes in I'll also reference it in the wiki page at https://github.com/OE4T/meta-tegra/wiki/Using-device-tree-overlays or I could work on a reorg/retitle of this page since it's about more than just devicetree overlays at this point.

# Commit Text
As discussed in [1], overlay source on JP5/6 targets appears to come only from the update capsule content in spi flash and not from either the content appended to the extlinux dtb.  This means if a slot switch occurs the devicetree overlay content used will match the last capsule update as opposed to the content overlayed on the dtb file referenced in extlinux.conf.  This also means slot switches don't apply dtb overlay changes when using slot switching instead of capsule update as a software update strategy for non bootloader components (see the TEGRA_SWUPDATE_BOOTLOADER_INSTALL_ONLY_IF_DIFFERENT feature at [2] for example).

With this patch, add support for writing the OVERLAYS value in the extlinux.conf file.  Specifiying

```
UBOOT_EXTLINUX_FDT = "/boot/${DTBFILE}"
USE_OVERLAYS_IN_EXTLINUX = "1"
```
in your local.conf or machine config will
* Copy all .dtbo files in TEGRA_PLUGIN_MANAGER_OVERLAYS list into the /boot directory of the rootfs when building the l4t-launcher-extlinux.
* Reference each .dtbo file in the extlinux.conf file, applying it as a part of the ExtLinuxBoot process in L4TLauncher.

1: https://matrix.to/#/!YBfWVpJwNVtkmqVCPS:gitter.im/$OJAkyoJCMQDfiamxJGULUseBv7vgH2fJy9cVLMbhh4g?via=gitter.im&via=matrix.org&via=3dvisionlabs.com
2: https://github.com/OE4T/tegra-demo-distro/tree/master/layers/meta-tegrademo/dynamic-layers/meta-swupdate#tegra_swupdate_bootloader_install_only_if_different

# Testing

Testing on master with jetson-orin-nano-devkit-nvme

1. Set in the local.conf:
```
UBOOT_EXTLINUX_FDT = "/boot/${DTBFILE}"
USE_OVERLAYS_IN_EXTLINUX = "1"
IMAGE_INSTALL:append = " dtc"
```

2. After boot, generate a DTS copy of the first overlay using logic like this:
```
cat /boot/extlinux/extlinux.conf | sed -n 's/.*OVERLAYS[[:space:]]\+\([^,]*\).*/\1/p' | xargs cat | dtc -I dtb -O dts >  /boot/first-overlay-original.dts && cp /boot/first-overlay-original.dts /boot/first-overlay-modified.dts
```
3. Modify the /boot/first-overlay-modified.dts by adding a line `test = "overlay-modified"`.  The resulting difference should look like this:
```
diff /boot/first-overlay-original.dts /boot/first-overlay-modified.dts
--- /boot/first-overlay-original.dts
+++ /boot/first-overlay-modified.dts
@@ -7,6 +7,7 @@
                target-path = "/";

                __overlay__ {
+                        test = "overlay-modified";

                        reserved-memory {
                                #address-cells = <0x02>;

```
4. Convert the modified dts file into the first overlay in the OVERLAYS list:
```
dtc -I dts -O dtb -o /boot/first-overlay-modified.dtbo  /boot/first-overlay-modified.dts 
cat /boot/extlinux/extlinux.conf | sed -n 's/.*OVERLAYS[[:space:]]\+\([^,]*\).*/\1/p' | xargs cp /boot/first-overlay-modified.dtbo
```
5. reboot
6. Verify the test marker is added to the device-tree from the overlay
```
root@jetson-orin-nano-devkit-nvme:~# cat /proc/device-tree/test
overlay-modified
```

review.body:
I have some notes in-line, but overall...

I'd appreciate it if this could be split into multiple commits.

1.  Refactor the library functions
2. Get rid of the `do_concat_dtb_overlays` function, since we've established that it's completely unnecessary - L4TLauncher doesn't process overlays concatenated to the kernel DTB that it reads, either from the extlinux config, nor from the android kernel-dtb partition. Instead, just install the dtb if UBOOT_EXTLINUX_FDT is set.
3. Add the overlay support in the extlinux config. This should be kept separate from `TEGRA_PLUGIN_MANAGER_OVERLAYS`, since the extlinux ones are applied *in addition* to the ones attached to the bootloader's DTB.
4. Maybe switch to setting `UBOOT_EXTLINUX_FDT` by default for the device tree, too, for consistency. Just seems odd to have overlays in the config with out the base device tree.

And can you verify that all this works with UEFI signing enabled - i.e., that signing happens for all the overlays, so they all get their `.dtbo.sig` files installed?

pull_request.title: l4t-extlinux-config: add support for OVERLAYS
pull_request.body:
This PR adds support for OVERLAYS in extlinux.conf to meta-tegra.  I haven't found this feature officially documented anywhere but it's referenced in forums like https://forums.developer.nvidia.com/t/place-custom-overlay-file-via-extlinux-conf/298287.  This feature is useful for anyone who wants to be able to modify devicetree overlays listed in `TEGRA_PLUGIN_MANAGER_OVERLAYS` without the necessity to do a capsule update, either by hand modifying in their `/boot` directory or using the `TEGRA_SWUPDATE_BOOTLOADER_INSTALL_ONLY_IF_DIFFERENT` feature of the [swupdate demo](https://github.com/OE4T/tegra-demo-distro/tree/master/layers/meta-tegrademo/dynamic-layers/meta-swupdate#tegra_swupdate_bootloader_install_only_if_different).

If/when this commit goes in I have a backport I'm planning for r35 branches which will also pull in a rebased commit from r36 branches of edk2-nvidia to support this on Jetpack 5 targets as well.  I've tested to ensure this works on kirkstone, see https://github.com/OE4T/meta-tegra/compare/kirkstone...Trellis-Logic:meta-tegra:kirkstone+overlays-extlinux-feature?expand=1 for preview. This means all device tree content should be able to be synchronized with rootfs content across the Jetpack 5/6 release series.

For those who don't specify `USE_OVERLAYS_IN_EXTLINUX = "1"` there should be no change with this PR, devicetree overlays will continue to come from spiflash only.

One thing I didn't take on with this task but could... I don't believe the logic in `do_concat_dtb_overlays` [here](https://github.com/OE4T/meta-tegra/blob/651e0898cb47ccc86c0ed5c7617fcfeadd7fda1f/recipes-bsp/uefi/l4t-launcher-extlinux.bb#L50-L55) actually is used by anything as far as I can tell. I could rename this function to reference its dual use for copying overlays or remove the concatenate part.

If/when this goes in I'll also reference it in the wiki page at https://github.com/OE4T/meta-tegra/wiki/Using-device-tree-overlays or I could work on a reorg/retitle of this page since it's about more than just devicetree overlays at this point.

# Commit Text
As discussed in [1], overlay source on JP5/6 targets appears to come only from the update capsule content in spi flash and not from either the content appended to the extlinux dtb.  This means if a slot switch occurs the devicetree overlay content used will match the last capsule update as opposed to the content overlayed on the dtb file referenced in extlinux.conf.  This also means slot switches don't apply dtb overlay changes when using slot switching instead of capsule update as a software update strategy for non bootloader components (see the TEGRA_SWUPDATE_BOOTLOADER_INSTALL_ONLY_IF_DIFFERENT feature at [2] for example).

With this patch, add support for writing the OVERLAYS value in the extlinux.conf file.  Specifiying

```
UBOOT_EXTLINUX_FDT = "/boot/${DTBFILE}"
USE_OVERLAYS_IN_EXTLINUX = "1"
```
in your local.conf or machine config will
* Copy all .dtbo files in TEGRA_PLUGIN_MANAGER_OVERLAYS list into the /boot directory of the rootfs when building the l4t-launcher-extlinux.
* Reference each .dtbo file in the extlinux.conf file, applying it as a part of the ExtLinuxBoot process in L4TLauncher.

1: https://matrix.to/#/!YBfWVpJwNVtkmqVCPS:gitter.im/$OJAkyoJCMQDfiamxJGULUseBv7vgH2fJy9cVLMbhh4g?via=gitter.im&via=matrix.org&via=3dvisionlabs.com
2: https://github.com/OE4T/tegra-demo-distro/tree/master/layers/meta-tegrademo/dynamic-layers/meta-swupdate#tegra_swupdate_bootloader_install_only_if_different

# Testing

Testing on master with jetson-orin-nano-devkit-nvme

1. Set in the local.conf:
```
UBOOT_EXTLINUX_FDT = "/boot/${DTBFILE}"
USE_OVERLAYS_IN_EXTLINUX = "1"
IMAGE_INSTALL:append = " dtc"
```

2. After boot, generate a DTS copy of the first overlay using logic like this:
```
cat /boot/extlinux/extlinux.conf | sed -n 's/.*OVERLAYS[[:space:]]\+\([^,]*\).*/\1/p' | xargs cat | dtc -I dtb -O dts >  /boot/first-overlay-original.dts && cp /boot/first-overlay-original.dts /boot/first-overlay-modified.dts
```
3. Modify the /boot/first-overlay-modified.dts by adding a line `test = "overlay-modified"`.  The resulting difference should look like this:
```
diff /boot/first-overlay-original.dts /boot/first-overlay-modified.dts
--- /boot/first-overlay-original.dts
+++ /boot/first-overlay-modified.dts
@@ -7,6 +7,7 @@
                target-path = "/";

                __overlay__ {
+                        test = "overlay-modified";

                        reserved-memory {
                                #address-cells = <0x02>;

```
4. Convert the modified dts file into the first overlay in the OVERLAYS list:
```
dtc -I dts -O dtb -o /boot/first-overlay-modified.dtbo  /boot/first-overlay-modified.dts 
cat /boot/extlinux/extlinux.conf | sed -n 's/.*OVERLAYS[[:space:]]\+\([^,]*\).*/\1/p' | xargs cp /boot/first-overlay-modified.dtbo
```
5. reboot
6. Verify the test marker is added to the device-tree from the overlay
```
root@jetson-orin-nano-devkit-nvme:~# cat /proc/device-tree/test
overlay-modified
```

## ðŸŽ¨ B2B Marketplace Frontend Transformation

This PR completes the frontend transformation from collectibles auctions to a hyperlocal B2B surplus marketplace, implementing the core user workflows for business equipment, construction materials, and commercial goods.

### ðŸš€ **New Pages & Features**

**Homepage Transformation** (`Index.tsx`)
- âœ… B2B-focused hero section with regional market emphasis
- âœ… Business equipment categories (Construction, Restaurant, Office, Municipal)
- âœ… "Find Lots Near You" with location-based browsing
- âœ… Success stories from local businesses

**Regional Browsing** (`RegionPage.tsx`)
- âœ… Distance-based filtering (5, 15, 30+ miles)
- âœ… Hyperlocal lot discovery with PostGIS integration
- âœ… Business verification tier badges (T0-T3)
- âœ… Real-time location detection and region selection

**Lot Creation** (`CreateLotPage.tsx`)
- âœ… Comprehensive B2B lot creation form
- âœ… Business-specific fields (condition, dimensions, specifications)
- âœ… Category selection for target verticals
- âœ… Pickup location and timeframe settings
- âœ… Reserve pricing and auction duration controls

**QR Scanner** (`QRScannerPage.tsx`)
- âœ… Camera-based QR code scanning for pickup verification
- âœ… Manual code entry fallback option
- âœ… Integration with pickup confirmation Edge Function
- âœ… Automatic seller payout trigger

**Updated Routing** (`App.tsx`)
- âœ… `/r/:regionSlug` - Regional marketplace browsing
- âœ… `/sell/new` - Create new B2B lot
- âœ… `/pickup/:lotId/scan` - QR pickup verification

Refactor email link sign-in and update configurations

This commit refactors the email link sign-in process for both Android and iOS platforms.

Key changes include:
- Updated Firebase Hosting `apple-app-site-association` paths from `/tyche/signin` to `/sign-in/*`.
- Modified Android Manifest intent filter path prefix for sign-in from `/signin` to `/sign-in`.
- Introduced `IosBundleIdProvider` in Android core and its implementation `LocalIosBundleIdProvider` to provide the iOS bundle ID. This is now used in `AuthenticationFirebaseDataSource` for setting Android package name and iOS bundle ID in `ActionCodeSettings`.
- Added `AndroidPackageNameProvider` in iOS Core and its implementation `LocalAndroidPackageNameProvider` to provide the Android package name. This is used in `AuthenticationFirebaseDataSource` for `ActionCodeSettings`.
- Updated `signInLinkUrlTemplate` in `gradle.properties` and `AppConfig.xcconfig` to use `/sign-in/` path.
- Added `iosBundleId` to `gradle.properties` and `ANDROID_PACKAGE_NAME` to `AppConfig.xcconfig`.
- Moved `emailLinkSignInView` composable content from `EmailLinkSignInViewProvider.kt` (deleted) to `SignInWithEmailLinkNavViewProvider.kt` and updated deep link URI pattern.
- Updated string resources for account verification description.
- Removed an unnecessary `println` statement in `RetrofitExceptionHandler.kt`.
- Added `AppDelegate.swift` in the iOS project to configure FirebaseApp.
- Updated project files to include new provider files and `AppDelegate.swift`.

pull_request.title: Add status subresource to StorageProfile
pull_request.body:
We have been observing flaky failures in the StorageProfile functional tests.

The root cause appears to be a race condition. Each test resets the spec upon completion, but the controller is likely still processing the previous state when the next test begins. Without a status field, the test has no way to confirm that the controller has finished reconciling the previous state.

This change introduces a status subresource to the StorageProfile. This allows tests and clients to observe the resource's actual state and wait for the status field to be populated - signaling that reconciliation is complete before proceeding.

The implementation includes:

1. Adding the +kubebuilder:subresource:status annotation to the StorageProfile type.
2. Updating the controller to handle status updates separately from the spec.
3. Regenerating the CRD to support the status subresource.

pull_request.title: Add status subresource to StorageProfile
pull_request.body:
We have been observing flaky failures in the StorageProfile functional tests.

The root cause appears to be a race condition. Each test resets the spec upon completion, but the controller is likely still processing the previous state when the next test begins. Without a status field, the test has no way to confirm that the controller has finished reconciling the previous state.

This change introduces a status subresource to the StorageProfile. This allows tests and clients to observe the resource's actual state and wait for the status field to be populated - signaling that reconciliation is complete before proceeding.

The implementation includes:

1. Adding the +kubebuilder:subresource:status annotation to the StorageProfile type.
2. Updating the controller to handle status updates separately from the spec.
3. Regenerating the CRD to support the status subresource.

Jest 30.0.1

What's Changed

Features

  • [jest-resolver] Implement the defaultAsyncResolver (#15679)

Fixes

  • [jest-resolver] Resolve builtin modules correctly (#15683)
  • [jest-environment-node, jest-util] Avoid setting globals cleanup protection symbol when feature is off (#15684)

New Contributors

Full Changelog: https://github.com/jestjs/jest/blob/main/CHANGELOG.md

Jest 30

Today we are happy to announce the release of Jest 30. This release features a substantial number of changes, fixes, and improvements. While it is one of the largest major releases of Jest ever, we admit that three years for a major release is too long. In the future, we are aiming to make more frequent major releases to keep Jest great for the next decade.

If you want to skip all the news and just get going, run npm install jest@^30.0.0 and follow the migration guide: Upgrading from Jest 29 to 30.

Read the full blog post

Features

  • [*] Renamed globalsCleanupMode to globalsCleanup and --waitNextEventLoopTurnForUnhandledRejectionEvents to --waitForUnhandledRejections
